- CSS custom properties are useful if you need SASS variables but don't happen to have SASS
- notice that `largeSize` is calculated from `normalSize`
- notice also that you can change the colors and multiple elements change colors:##custompropsandcalc
- HTML and CSS:
	---------------------------
	<!DOCTYPE html>
	<html lang="en">

	<head>
		<meta charset="UTF-8">
		<meta name="viewport" content="width=device-width, initial-scale=1.0">
		<title>CSS Properties</title>
		<style>
			body {
				padding: 0 20px;
			}
			:root {
				--normalSize: 1em;
				--largeSize: calc(var(--normalSize) * 1.3);
				--colorBad: tomato;
				--colorWarn: darkorange;
				--colorGood: darkgreen;
			}

			p.errorMessage {
				font-size: var(--largeSize);
				color: var(--colorBad);
			}

			p.careful {
				font-size: var(--normalSize);
				color: var(--colorWarn);
			}

			p.success {
				font-size: var(--normalSize);
				color: var(--colorGood);
			}

			h1.error {
				color: var(--colorBad);
			}

			h1.warning {
				color: var(--colorWarn);
			}

			h1.successHeader {
				color: var(--colorGood);
			}
		</style>
	</head>

	<body>
		<h1 class="error">Message:</h1>
		<p class="errorMessage">This is an error.</p>
		<hr>
		<h1 class="warning">Message:</h1>
		<p class="careful">This is an warning.</p>
		<hr>
		<h1 class="successHeader">Message:</h1>
		<p class="success">Congratulations.</p>
	</body>

	</html>
	---------------------------

- note that that `?` in the regular expression is a non-greedy expression so that the regex only selects each word and not the beginning of the first word to the end of the last word##replaceJavascriptRegexok
- test.js
	----------------------------------
	const regex = /(\*.*?\*)/;
	const sentence = "Using Bootstrap Grid means writing more *HTML*. Using CSS Grid means writing more *CSS*.";

	const replaceAllRegex = (text, regex, replace) => text.replace(new RegExp(regex, 'g'), replace);

	const clozeSentence = replaceAllRegex(sentence, regex, '[_________]');

	console.log(regex);
	console.log(sentence);
	console.log(clozeSentence);
