- useful features of TypeScript
	- **interfaces**
		- you can define objects so that they must have a specific type for each property, errors will be reported in your editor:##badscoresan
		- when you use variables that have interface types, VSCode/TypeScript will give you accurate information in JavaScript code and JSX regarding which properties you are allowed to use and what types these properties have:##typescriptintellisense
	- **enums**
		- with enums you can define a list of allowed values for a property##theenumexamples
		- enums are useful for conditional rendering, but note if you want to display their value, you need to use the enum itself as an array and pass the value of the variable as the index:##usingeneums
- use interfaces/models to convert unstructured data (e.g. from an API) into structured data: 
	- first load raw book data directly:
		-----------------------------------------
		import { useEffect, useState } from 'react';
		import axios from 'axios';

		const url = 'https://gutendex.com/books/?search=paris';

		function App() {
			const [books, setBooks] = useState([]);

			useEffect(() => {
				(async () => {
					setBooks((await axios.get(url)).data.results);
				})();
			}, []);

			return (
				<div className="App">
					{books.length === 0 ? (
						<div>Loading...</div>
					) : (
						<h2>There are {books.length} books:</h2>
					)}
				</div>
			);
		}

		export default App;
		-----------------------------------------
	- now list out the books and display properties
	- note the TypeScript starts to complain that it does not know the types, which means you have unstructured data:##typesshowsdirtydata
	- if you just display `book.authors[0]` the books that have no authors will cause an error
	- so you need to code logic into JSX which you should avoid as much as possible
	- TypeScript also informs us that authors is not known for certain##notforscertain
	- a solution to this is to create TypeScript interfaces and models which implement these interfaces
		- **src/interfaces.tsx**
			----------------------------------
			export interface IBook {
				title: string;
				author: string;
			}			
			----------------------------------
		- **src/bookModel.ts**
			----------------------------------
			import { IBook } from './interfaces';

			export const getBooks = (rawBooks: any[]) => {
				const books: IBook[] = [];
				rawBooks.forEach((rawBook: any) => {
					const book: IBook = {
						title: rawBook.title,
						author: rawBook.authors.length > 0 ? rawBook.authors[0].name : '(unknown)'
					}
					books.push(book);
				});

				return books;
			}			
			----------------------------------
		- **App.tsx**
			-------------------------------------
			import { IBook } from './data/interfaces';
			import { getBooks } from './data/bookModel'; 

			useEffect(() => {
				(async () => {
					const rawBooks = (await axios.get(url)).data.results;
					const _books: IBook[] = getBooks(rawBooks);
					setBooks(_books);
				})();
			}, []);
			-------------------------------------
		- note now that TypeScript is complaining in a cryptic way that we are trying to save an array of objects of type IBook into an untyped array ##nevertypescript
		- the solution for this is to inform TypeScript that our state variable `books` is an array of type IBooks
		- now in JSX, we have a clean and structured array of objects that always have a title and always have an author, which gives us the assurance that we will not receive errors because of missing data, wrong types, etc.:##alwaystitleauth

