- background of website servers / JavaScript frameworks
	- static sites
		- since ca. 1989
		- put static files on the server which are served 1-to-1 to browsers
	- server-side rendered sites
		- since ca. 1993 with e.g. CGI/Perl
		- early general website servers still uses today are Apache (1995) and nginx (2002)
		- a web server dynamically renders files on the server machine and serves the results to the browser via the Internet
		- enables websites to be generated on-the-fly from databases
		- enables sites to perform authentication and authorization of users
		- PHP, Ruby-on-Rails, ASP.NET, Django(Python)
		- often seen as complete web technology stacks, e.g. LAMP (Linux, Apache, MySQL, PHP) or .NET (Windows, IIS, SQL Server, C#)
		- **Node/Express** + templating engines such as **EJS**, Pug, Mustache, Dust
			- note: Pug was formerly called Jade
	- client-side rendering
		- since ca. 2013 with JavaScript frameworks such as **React**, Vue.js, Angular
		- send HTML and JavaScript to browsers and then let that JavaScript dynamically render a **single-page-application**
	- server-side-rendered sites *revisited*
		- since ca. 2016 with e.g. Next.js
		- take programming patterns (such as React) from the frontend to the backend
		- render components on the server instead in the browser
		- advantages
			- SEO and security of server-side
			- yet with the new programming paradigms of JavaScript frameworks
	- static sites *revisited*
		- since ca. 2016 with the **Jamstack philosophy**
		- difference: static-site generators create sites dynamically which are then served statically
			- all content is prerendered into static files
		- CDN providers such as **Netlify** and **Vercel** serve these static files
		- advantages
			- extremely fast sites from geolocated servers
			- extremely secure
				- "you can't have your database hacked when you don't have a database"
				- "you don't have any backend bugs when you don't have a backend"
		- data exists on other servers, in the cloud on data-dedicated servers 
			- this is where the term **headless** comes from, e.g. headless content management system, i.e. only the data "body", no frontend "head"
		- data is accessed and manipulated from static sites via REST APIs and GraphQL
	- mix-and-match
		- the most interesting frameworks today generate all three paradigms: server-side, client-side, static
			- for React: Next.js, Gatsby
			- for Vue.js: Nuxt
			- for Angular: Angular Universal
- this howto has four purposes:
	- it is a useful way to build a small, data-driven website that collects data from various sources and displays it in the browser, e.g. as a development tool or as some kind of information dashboard site
	- it is a project that will give us a better idea and appreciation of what is behind various frameworks that we use, such as React, Next.js, Gatsby, Vue.js, Angular, and since we are now on the backend, of what one can do with languages such as PHP, C#, Java, Go, and Rust when building the backends of websites
	- it expands our understanding of what one can do with Node and Express since, while we are still in JavaScript as we were when writing JS/DOM and React sites, we are now on the backend and thus have many more opportunities of what our code can effect on computers and on the web
	- this code can be the beginning of our own JavaScript framework, either with a general purpose or a specific purpose
		- some job ads I have seen ask for skills in Node/Express/JavaScript and general web technology since they have written their own web framwork for some niche business area and need developers to maintain and expand it
- specifically, this howto takes you step-by-step to show you how to use Node/Express to create data-driven, server-side generated website
	- when we were developing JavaScript/DOM sites, our JavaScript code was client-side, so what was our server?
		- one could say that the server was simply our operating system, or the file system which sent HTML files directly to our browser one-to-one
		- we often used VSCode Live-Server which is software that serves HTML/CSS/JavaScript files not from the file system but via localhost and a specific port (5500)
			- Live Server is in effect simply a server like the one we are building today, but in the form of a VSCode extension
	- but now we are working in Node, our JavaScript code is no longer in the browser but in the server
		- with Node/Express we no longer have to send HTML/CSS/JavaScript files one-to-one to the browser
		- have now have complete control over what we send to the browser
		- we can manipulate it before it is sent
		- we can determine if someone is logged in and only send them HTML/CSS/JavaScript code they are allowed to see and use
		- we can render the HTML based on various kinds of template engines before the HTML is sent to the browser, e.g. EJS, mustache
		- we can create content management systems so that any new `.md` file that we (or even a non-developer employee) copies to a directory becomes a new page on the site or a new article in the site
