- **Why use TypeScript instead of JavaScript?**
	- TypeScript gives structure to JavaScript, makes it less **error-prone**, **more stabile** and **easier to test**
	- all JavaScript is syntactically valid TypeScript
		- this means that TypeScript is quite incremental, i.e. **you could create a React site in TypeScript and simply program in JavaScript**, adding only the TypeScript as you learn it
			- but even if you program in 100% JavaScript, you will still notice that TypeScript is there in the background protecting you from sloppy errors like this:##justjavascriptok
		- one way to understand this is to realize that TypeScript transpiles to JavaScript at build time
			- **TypeScript exists only as you develop and at build time, not in the final build code**
				- as you develop, VSCode will give you TypeScript errors
				- at build time, you will have a successful build only when you have no TypeScript errors
					- this means **when your TypeScript code builds successfully, all that is left is 100% efficient JavaScript that knows nothing about TypeScript**
					- e.g. if you create a site in TypeScript and publish it at Netlify, **the code that is running at Netlify is 100% JavaScript** and knows nothing about TypeScript
					- this means that **using TypeScript produces code that is simply JavaScript** and so **code you create with TypeScript can run anywhere JavaScript runs**
			- to understand this better, note that when the following code builds, **more than half of the TypeScript code does not even get transpiled** into JavaScript, and while the compiled JavaScript would technically run without errors, **TypeScript will not compile it since it violates the Type relationships defined by the user**##thewontwokrok
		- so while sites you build with TypeScript will run anywhere JavaScript runs, **the JavaScript that TypeScript creates safely conforms to a complex type structure that you defined in your original code**, which only exists in your original TypeScript files
- **What makes TypeScript so difficult for JavaScript programmers?**
	- TypeScript contains many complex, mostly object-oriented-based patterns and concepts, e.g. **generics**, **type casting**, **type guarding**, **namespaces**
		- here is an example of generics and casting in a function I wrote for my open source framework in which many types of items which inherit from a parent class can use this one function by informing it which Types it should use##typescriptcompl
		- one reason why TypeScript excels at object-oriented patterns is that **TypeScript was created by Microsoft systems architect Anders Hejlsberg who also created C#** back in 2001
			- in essense, TypeScript is Microsoft's attempt to get JavaScript to act like and be more compatible with C#
		- these advanced features of TypeScript can make it a complex language to learn for JavaScript programmers, particularly JavaScript programmers who are not very familiar with object-oriented programming patterns
		- in addition, getting JavaScript to behave like C# doesn't come without odd errors that you can spend much time trying to resolve, e.g.:##typescriptnever
		- or this:##thecannot
- **So how to get started with TypeScript that is useful, efficient but avoids the difficult complexities of TypeScript?**		
	- the following is a **low-hanging-fruit approach to TypeScript** i.e. a way to use and benefit from the language without have to yet deal with its more complex OOP concepts and functionality
		1. to begin with, **use only the following features**:
			- **basic types** (string, number, boolean, string[], number[], boolean[])
			- **interfaces**
			- **enums**
			- none of these features require object-oriented expertise
			- using only these three features of TypeScript will provide your application with much more structure, security and useful intellisense while developing that you don't get from JavaScript
				- as you master and become comfortable with these features, you can explore the more complex features of TypeScript
		2. **use Vite** to create a React site in seconds that is completely set up with TypeScript and ready to develop
			- this bypasses much of the complexity that was often associated with TypeScript: getting it set up in your development environment##howtoreactvitekjsk
- **What we will build**
	- a frontend React site that imports an array of objects as a JSON file and displays the content to the screen
	- the JSON file will contain an array of book objects that have non-uniform properties which we must handle according to specific rules
		- rule: books must have the following properties
			- id, number
			- title, string
			- description, string
			- language, string
			- yearMonth, string
			- numberInStock, number
		- rule: language property value must be either "english" or "french"
			- if language is blank or missing, then assign value "english"
			- for any other value, mark as error that only administrators can see
		- rule: no property can be empty
			- if empty, then mark as error
		- rule: all numbers must be numbers
			- if number is string and can be converted to number (e.g. "4") then convert it
			- if number is not number (e.g. "none" or "n/a"), mark as error that only administrators can see
