					- **note** that even though TypeScript is insuring that currentUser has a property username in JSX
						- this is only at develop time, not at run time
						- at run time, all of these types are gone since at run time we are running JavaScript, not TypeScript
						- therefore it can very well be that our frontend receives a currentUser object from the backend that does not have a username property and our code will break at run time
						- hence, even though we use TypeScript to protect our code from **ourselves**, TypeScript does not protect our code from the real world at run time
						- for that, we need to add validation and code the reacts to the case that currentUser may not have a property called username at run time
						- ideally we would do this in our model, so that our app can always depend on getting well-formed data and can concentrate on data presentation instead of data-cleansing and data-validation which should happen in the data model
