- in React you have **normal variables** and **state variables**
	- create a Vite site and show example of each:
		----------------------------------------
		import { useState } from 'react';
		import './App.css';

		function App() {
			const [count, setCount] = useState(0);

		  let score = 0;
		  const handleIncreaseScoreButton = () => {
			score++;  
			console.log(score);
		  }

			return (
				<div className="App">
					<div className="card">
						<button onClick={() => setCount((count) => count + 1)}>
							count is {count}
						</button>
				<hr/>
				<button onClick={() => handleIncreaseScoreButton()}>increase score: {score}</button>
					</div>
				</div>
			);
		}

		export default App;		
		----------------------------------------
	- note that **count** changes when you click the button but **score** doesn't
		- because count is a **state variable**
		- but score is a **normal variable**
	- change score to a state variable and see that the button click can change it:
		--------------------------------------
		import { useState } from 'react';
		import './App.css';

		function App() {
			const [count, setCount] = useState(0);
			const [score, setScore] = useState(0);

			const handleIncreaseScoreButton = () => {
			const _score = score + 1;
				setScore(_score);
				if (_score >= 10) {
					setCount(0);
				}
			};

			return (
				<div className="App">
					<div className="card">
						<button onClick={() => setCount((count) => count + 1)}>
							count is {count}
						</button>
						<hr />
						<button onClick={() => handleIncreaseScoreButton()}>
							increase score: {score}
						</button>
					</div>
				</div>
			);
		}

		export default App;		
		--------------------------------------
	- **QUESTION:** Why do we have an extra variable **_score**?
		- **ANSWER:** Because the **setScore()** function does not set the value of the state variable immediately and so in the next line, the value has not changed yet, so we have to use a normal variable which changes its value immediately, and then use this value in the two cases.
- state variables are very useful because JSX will automatically **react** to changes in state variables, which is why the framework is called **React**
	- note you can have as much logic based on state variables as you want
		- CHALLENGE: when both count and score are not zero, display a message "both are not zero"
		- CHALLENGE: when score is greater or equal to 10, make the App element background red
- one important aspect you have to remember about state variables is that they are **immutable**
	- this means that they cannot change value
		- QUESTION: but if they cannot change value, how do you change their value so that JSX can react to them?
		- ANSWER: you always have to **replace them with a new value**
			- this is automatic with **string, number and boolean** value since the maximum size they take up is known and hence they are stored on the **stack** in memory 
				- so `setScore(0)` and `setCount(0)` both the value of the number that was there before
			- but this is not automatic with **arrays** and **objects** which are just pointers on the state to their values which lie on the **heap**
			- note that if you don't **send a copy** of an array of object (typically done with the spread operator) into the set function of a state variable, it will not update the variable
