- **background**
	- when you create a JS/DOM site with Vite, your HTML is no longer in HTML files but rather **output as template strings**
	- this makes it impossible to simply include an onclick attribute in HTML elements and then handle these events in a function in your JavaScript modules
	- there is a hack workaround for this ([see the code here](https://github.com/edwardtanguay/et005-vite-jsdom-jsonserver/tree/onclick-works-with-handler-function-in-indexhtml)) where you can put your event-handling functions in the **index.html** file but the problem with this is:
		- 1. you no longer have your event handlers connected to the code in which they the events are fired
		- 2. if you use TypeScript, then you no longer have TypeScript protectiong in **index.html** file which is merely a shell to start your actual application where your event handlers logically should reside
	- while this code is a good start for e.g. developing a TS/DOM framework, it also shows the limitations of JS/DOM and can be used to demonstrate what React/JSX solves regarding the ease of creating event-handling functions inside components
		- note that the directory structure is based on that of React sites
	- the backend for this site is **json-server**
