- in general, in 2023 and beyond, I always use arrow functions
	- the syntax is more succinct
	- they can be written as one-liners
	- **example1.js**
		---------------------------------------------------------
		const shuffle = (items) => {
			for (let i = items.length - 1; i > 0; i--) {
				const j = Math.floor(Math.random() * (i + 1));
				const temp = items[i];
				items[i] = items[j];
				items[j] = temp;
			}
		};

		const frameworks = ["React", "Angular", "Vue.js", "Next.js", "Knockout", "Svelte", "SolidJS", "Gatsby", "Remix", "Astro" ];

		console.log(frameworks);
		shuffle(frameworks);
		console.log(frameworks);		
		---------------------------------------------------------
	- output:##thearrow1
- one reason one still might use **classic functions** is if you have a simple one-file script and want to keep long functions out of the way at the **bottom of the file**
	- this **doesn't work with arrow functions**, since they are variables and so can't be used until they are defined
	- **example2.js**
		----------------------------------------------------
		const frameworks = ["React", "Angular", "Vue.js", "Next.js", "Knockout", "Svelte", "SolidJS", "Gatsby", "Remix", "Astro" ];

		console.log(frameworks);
		shuffle(frameworks);
		console.log(frameworks);

		// long functions

		const shuffle = (items) => {
			for (let i = items.length - 1; i > 0; i--) {
				const j = Math.floor(Math.random() * (i + 1));
				const temp = items[i];
				items[i] = items[j];
				items[j] = temp;
			}
		};		
		----------------------------------------------------
	- output:##arrowfunctionnotwokrjkjing
- so in this case, if you transform these functions at the bottom of your file to **classic functions**, then you can call them before they are defined
	- this works because classic functions are automatically **[hoisted](https://linuxhint.com/function-hoisting-in-javascript)** to the top of the file
	- **example3.js**
		---------------------------------------------
		const frameworks = ["React", "Angular", "Vue.js", "Next.js", "Knockout", "Svelte", "SolidJS", "Gatsby", "Remix", "Astro" ];

		console.log(frameworks);
		shuffle(frameworks);
		console.log(frameworks);

		// long functions

		function shuffle (items) {
			for (let i = items.length - 1; i > 0; i--) {
				const j = Math.floor(Math.random() * (i + 1));
				const temp = items[i];
				items[i] = items[j];
				items[j] = temp;
			}
		};
		---------------------------------------------
	- output:##theaginskjein
- but all of **these issues are moot** from a practical point of view, since as **modern JavaScript developers** we program almost exclusively with JavaScript **ES6 modules** which use **import** and **export** commands to enable you to access the functions you need **from other files** such as libraries
	- all **JavaScript frameworks** use modules in this way
	- the simplest example of solving the above problem using modules is to do the following:
		- create new directory
		- create an npm project 
			- `npm init -y`
			- this simply creates a simple **package.json** file
			- add `"type": "module",` to the list of properties
		- your **package.json** should then look like this
			--------------------------------------------
			{
				"name": "et003-basic-javascript-modules",
				"version": "1.0.0",
				"description": "",
				"type": "module",
				"main": "tools.js",
				"scripts": {
					"test": "echo \"Error: no test specified\" && exit 1"
				},
				"keywords": [],
				"author": "",
				"license": "ISC"
			}
			--------------------------------------------
		- **app.js**
			----------------------------------------------------
			import * as tools from './tools.js';

			const frameworks = ["React", "Angular", "Vue.js", "Next.js", "Knockout", "Svelte", "SolidJS", "Gatsby", "Remix", "Astro"];

			console.log(frameworks);
			tools.shuffle(frameworks);
			console.log(frameworks);
			----------------------------------------------------
		- **tools.js**
			----------------------------------------------
			export const shuffle = (items) => {
				for (let i = items.length - 1; i > 0; i--) {
					const j = Math.floor(Math.random() * (i + 1));
					const temp = items[i];
					items[i] = items[j];
					items[j] = temp;
				}
			};
			----------------------------------------------
		- the output:##thenodeappsokok
		- so with this module approach, you have one or more library files (e.g. **tools.js**) from which you **export** as many functions as you like
			- then from your main application files (e.g. **app.js**), you **import** your library files which gives you access to all of your functions
		- the above mini-app with module-based code can be found in [this repo](https://github.com/edwardtanguay/et003-basic-javascript-modules) 
- **TIP:** if you are learning JavaScript
	- **get to a point as fast as you can** where you are 
		- programming with **ES6 modules** (import/export)
		- either self-created projects such as the above
		- or **JavaScript frameworks** such as React, Angular, Vue.js, Next.js, Svelte, etc.
	- programming with **JavaScript modules** 
		- 1. solves these earlier problems of JavaScript such as 
			- variable collisions with global variables
			- JavaScript functions that are not available
		- 2. makes your code more organized
		- 3. makes your code easier to test

