	- so this solution works, but **what is the problem with this solution?**
		- 1. if we needed to use some data from employees and fetch some other data, then we would have to **call a callback inside a callback**
			- and if we needed to do that again, we would be three levels deep in callbacks, and so on
			- this is what is referred to as **callback hell**##referredascall
		- 2. if we needed to handle errors, we would have to send two callbacks to one function
	- so while this solution works, JavaScript was in need of a better way handle asynchronous data
		- this was solve with **promises** (2015) and **async/await** (2017) which we will see next
