- **most important skills, concepts and tools**	
	- **concepts**
		- **Q:** what is useRef?
			- **A:** useRef is a **hook** in React that allows you to create a mutable reference to a DOM element or a mutable value that persists across renders of a functional component
		- **Q:** what is a hook?
			- **A:** React hooks are JavaScript functions that help you manage component logic in a more organized and reusable way
				- they bring the logic of a particular code area into one place, and give you, the developer, values and functions to use in order to interact with this logic
				- a **hook** in functional programming is similar to a **class** in object-oriented programming
					- **hooks** give you functions and values that you can call
					- **classes** give you methods and settter/getter properties you can call
		- **Q:** why would I use useRef?
			- **A:** if there is some kind of DOM interaction that you can't do in React, you can use useRef to do it
				- for instance, it is not possible to programmatically set focus on an input field in React
				- so to do this, you use use**Ref** to get a **ref**erence to the underlying DOM input field 
				- then from React, you can use this **reference** just as you use the underlying DOM element, yet from the React context
		- **Q:** what security concerns should you have when you create a client-side login form in React
			- **A:** know that all of your code in your React site will be downloaded to the browser in the compiled .js file
				- so anyone who wanted to and had enough technical savvy, could find (1) your password and (2) your hidden content that you only shown when a correct password is entered
				- for high-profile company sites, this is of course a breach of security
				- for low-profile personal sites for which you want to (1) keep the content out of search machines and (2) make it near-impossible for non-technical people to view your content
				- for example, I often make a little website of our vacation itinerary with flight numbers, hotel, and later photos, etc. on a little website that my family and I can access with our phones, and we have to type in a 3-number pin to access it
					- this is super-easy to program
					- it keeps the site out of search machines
					- and if someone found the site, they would have to be quite technically skilled to find any of the information or photos that are shown when one knows the pin
	- **skills**
		- **Q:** how to reference and change a property on a DOM element with useRef
			- **A:** define a **ref** in the input element, then refer to it as <refName>.current
				- also make sure to tell TypeScript what type of element you expect it to be so you get code-completion and intellisense##thereftothsup
		- **Q:** when calling a function with onlick, what are the various ways to write the function
			- **A:** onClick={handleFormSubmit}
				- onClick={() => handleFormSubmit()}
				- onClick={(e) => handleFormSubmit(e)}
				- onChange={(e) => handleFormSubmit(e.target.value)}
		- **Q:** why is it when you create a React form that you sometimes can't type in the input box?
			- **A:** because you have connected the **value** attribute of the input box to the state variable for that field, but you haven't yet written the **onChange** event handler to change the text
		- **Q:** during debugging, how can you display an object in an alert
			- **A:** `alert(JSON.stringify(formData, null, 2));`
		- **Q:** what attribute can you add to an input box to make the cursor focus in it on page load
			- **A:** `autoFocus`
