- **===== MOST IMPORTANT CONCEPTS, SKILLS AND TOOLS =====**
	- **concepts**
		- **like many topics in web development, in what way is Sass a moving target?**
			- in most tutorials, classes and instruction videos you find, the older and soon-to-be-deprecated **@import** syntax is used
			- however, **@use/@forward** syntax has many advantages and will officially replace the older @import syntax
			- therefore, it is important to **know both** but **start new projects with @use/@forward**
		- **what is the 7-1 Sass folder structure pattern**
			- the official way to structure Sass files
			- the name come from **one** main.scss file and **seven** directories that contain various kinds of styling files##ohtheseven
		- **in what way could one say that Sass offers a "full spectrum of use"**
			- (1) Sass is often used as a **quick-and-easy solution** to improve on CSS
				- since Sass is easy to install (in Vite JS-DOM or Vite React sites, **npm i sass** and rename files to **.scss**) 
					- it has a low bar to entry
					- it is often used as a quick solution to have
						- **variables** ($color) 
						- **nested styles** (makes CSS much easier to read and manage)
			- (2) however, Sass is also used as a **professional solution** to create **custom, complex design systems** which includes
				- **modularity and organization**
					- splitting projects up into dozens of styling files
					- using @import or @use/@forward to manage how these files are included in the project
				- **code reuse** - @mixins and @functions to reuse code and dynamically create styles
				- **inheritance** - @extends to inherit styles
				- **built-in functions** - to build you rown themes and color and design palletes
				- **lists and maps** - to organized data in a programmatic way
				- **conditionals** - @if, @for, @each, @while to programmatically create styles
		- **when are Sass files prefixed by underscores**
			- when using @import syntax, files are prefixed with underscores in order to indicate that they are partials
			- this is not used with the @use/@forward syntax
			- note that even if you have a file name **_typography.scss**
				- you import it like this: `@import 'base/typography';`
		- **what advantages does the newer @use/@forward syntax have over the older @import syntax**
			- scoped variables
			- namespace management
			- improved performance
			- grouped importing with forwarding styles and index.scss
	- **skills**
		- **how to create numerous similar styles**
			- first define a list of e.g. colors
			- use @each to iterate through the colors and create a style based on each othem
		- **how to reduce code repetition**
			- use a @mixin which accepts parameters that return customized style chunks to use in other styles
	- **tools and commands**
		- Extension: SCSS Everywhere
		- 7-1 pattern
		- @mixin
		- @use
		- @use n
		- @use *
		- @forward
		- @mixin
		- @include
		- @content
		- index.scss
		- @function
		- @extend
		- @if, @for, @each, @while
		- Sass pseudo marker: &
		- mix()
