- **GOOD TO KNOW**
	- **why do we need unit testing at all?**
		- so we know that our functions work the way we expect them to work
		- so our site will not be published if tests don't pass
	- **what does unit testing test?**
		- unit testing tests the **smallest units** of an application, in most cases: **functions**
	- **when does one know one has written enough tests for a function to test it properly?**
		- this is in many cases a nuanced and debated issue
			- one can in most cases only approach 100% tested code
		- you want to test likely mistakes and edge cases: common issues, very large, very small amounts of data
	- **besides making your application more stable, what benefits does unit testing have?**		
		- enables you to make changes quickly regardless how large your code base is
			- change what you want to fix a bug or get a new feature to work
			- your tests will inform you if your changes cause anything to break in any other part of the application
		- helps new developers more quickly get up to speed in the project
			- if you want to know what the application is requied to do and not do, read the tests
			- this is even more true for end-to-end testing, which tests the entire application programmatically from the user's point of view
	- **what is the difference between Vitest and Jest**
		- "The two are API-compatible, so if you want to use Jest for some reason, no problem, everything I'm going to teach you about Vitest applies to Jest as well. But Vitest was made to go with Vite. It's made by the same people, it reads your Vite configuration, so we won't have to configure anything, it's just going to work out of the box for us, which seems pretty compelling to me. And Vite is meant to be a drop-in replacement for Jest. " - Brian Holt, Frontend Masters
