- **>>> 5. create and test the second function**
	- we will now add a second function to our tools
	- we will practice **Test-Driven Development (TDD)**
		- we will first write our test for this function
		- we will write as many expectations necessary to make sure 
			- when all expectations are fulfilled, the function does what it is supposed to do
		- we will then run the tests and see that the test for this function fails of course
		- we will then write our function until all tests pass
		- when all tests pass, we know we are finished
	- we want to test a function that will be called **sentencize()**
		- it should **take a string of text and convert it to a sentence**
			- note that this is a quite vague statement, e.g.
			- what exactly is considered a sentence?
			- does it have to have period at the end?
			- what about a question mark or exclamation mark?
			- what if it ends with a colon or semi-colon, is it still a sentence?
			- does it need to start with a capital letter?
			- what if it is a Spanish question that starts with a "¿"?
			- is a text that is only one character long considered a sentence?
			- is a text of all numbers considered a sentence?
			- what does the function return if e.g. one character is not considered a sentence?
				- return that character?
				- return a blank string?
				- return a text that shows some kind of error message?
				- throw an error from the function?
				- ignore it but write in a log file what text was sent leave it
			- and does the application allow right-to-left languages such as Arabic or extended UTF-8 languages such as Mandarin? if so, what rules do these languages have for a string being a sentence?
		- all of these questions depend on the context and goals of the application
			- in many cases in a work context, what you need to test is decided: 
				- by **program management** who determines the business logic of the application
				- together with the **developer team** when creating and discussing tasks for a sprint
			- in addition, a developer/tester should test edge cases such as
				- what happens when an **empty string**, an **extremely long string**, etc.
			- note also that **TypeScript** covers the basic tests, e.g.
				- you don't have to test what happens when you send e.g. a **number** or **boolean**
				- since TypeScript won't compile if you don't send a **string**
				- but realize that this only applies if you know that parameters are coming from inside the application
					- if parameters are coming directly from an external source such as an API, then you need to validate them with tests
					- but in general, you should have one point in your application where external data is cleaned and validated
						- once data gets through that entrance, it is considered trusted
	- let's say that program management and your developer team decide on the following functionality for the function **sentencize**:
		- (1) it receives a string as parameter
		- (2) if the first character is not capitalized, then capitalize it
		- (3) if the last character is not a period, question mark or exclamation mark, then add a period
		- (4) if the last character is a comma, semi-colon or colon, then remove it before added a period
		- (5) even if the string is one character or all numbers, treat it as a sentence, e.g. 
			- e.g. "who was it?" / "i" --> "Who was it?" / "I."
			- e.g. "how many?" / "23" -->  "How many?" / "23."
		- (6) if it begins with "¿", then capitalize the second character
			- e.g. "¿por qué?" --> "¿Por qué?"
	- here are is the test you could write that would arguable fulfill the above specifications:
