- **purpose of this howto**
	- the **target audience** of this howto are people who **use Vite React but have never used Next.js**
	- this howto will get you to the point where you can **chose Next.js instead of Vite** to build your next React website
		- this is a smart, future-oriented decision since when starting a new project, [the React team recommends you use Next.js](https://react.dev/learn/start-a-new-react-project) or some other **server-side** framework such as Remix or Gatsby, but doesn't mention Vite at all
		- it is particularly a good decision to learn Next.js, since Next.js is produced by **Vercel** 
			- **Vercel** provides a hosting platform for Next.js sites with a generous free tier that allows you to learn and take advantage of **server-side features** of Next.js
		- this trend toward using **server-side features** is not only the direction of React, but of the other major frameworks:
			- Vue --> [Nuxt](https://cubettech.com/resources/blog/why-might-you-consider-nuxt-for-your-next-vue-project)
			- Angular --> [Angular 17](https://dev.to/this-is-learning/exploring-angular-17-a-glimpse-into-the-future-of-web-development-part-3-2n4c)
			- Svelte --> [Svelte Kit](https://www.okupter.com/blog/svelte-vs-sveltekit-the-difference)
			- React --> [Next.js](https://radixweb.com/blog/nextjs-vs-react)
	- but **server-side** features
		- while they have their **advantages**
			- better **SEO**
			- **faster** load times
			- **progressive** loading experience
			- better **authorization** options (server-side middleware)
		- are also **not uncomplicated** and **require new ways of understanding** how website content is most efficiently delivered to the user
			- knowing **what is rendered on the server**, what is rendered on the client
			- being how to decide **what should be rendered on the server** vs. the client to improve user experience
			- understanding what kind of **backend environment** exists for the server-side features, e.g. file-system vs. [the edge](https://upstash.com/blog/vercel-edge)
			- understanding how **data-fetching** changes in a server-side environment and its increasingly close relationship to **page routing**
			- understanding how the **hydration process** works
			- understanding how **wrongly applying client-side paradigms** to server-side frameworks can cause problems
	- therefore 
		- this howto is **not about teaching you the server-side features** of Next.js
		- this howto is about 
			- showing you how to **do everything in Next.js that you know how to do in Vite React**
			- and hence, giving you the option to **choose Next.js instead of Vite React** for your future projects
			- which will give you the opportunity to **begin learning and using server-side features** in your future projects
- **what we will do in this howto**
	- as mentioned above, we will learn how to **do everything in Next.js that you know how to do in Vite React** including setting up a site the following features:
		- TypeScript
		- Tailwind
		- Sass
		- clickable menu that displays pages
		- items pages with an id in the URL
		- useContext
		- fetch API data with useEffect, useState, axios
		- button clicks and events
	- unlike Angular, Vue or Svelte, **Next.js uses the React library** and hence **much of Next.js is very familiar** to Vite React developers, e.g.
		- **components and props**
		- **JSX** with all its features such as **conditional rendering**, using **.map to display arrays**, **event handling**, etc.
		- **hooks** such as useState, useEffect, useContext, useReducer
	- however, with **Next.js** some aspects are completely different, e.g.
		- for routing, you don't use React Router but the **Next.js App Router**
	- and even if you only want to use client-side features, as is our goal in this howto, there are concepts you have to be aware of, e.g.
		- Next.js **components are server-side by default**, so if you want to use client-side functionality such as useState and useEffect, you have to explicitly define the component as client-side with `"use client"` on the first line##reactgraphic##thereactgraphiclibrary
