- **>>> 4. Refactor OOP in order to catch errors and be able to add features without added complexity**
	- currently our code works but 
		- (1) it quite error prone
			- e.g. if you don't capitalize the first character and execute "npm run test" it will create a page called Pagetest.tsx
			- e.g. if you only type `npm run cp`, it will create a page called Pageundefined.tsx##theundddef
		- (2) it is unstructured such that the more features we add, the more error prone and unmanageable it will become
			- e.g. adding the code to look through Nav.tsx and main.ts for certain text and insert text would be too complex without some sensible structure
	- in order to provide this needed structure in order to make our code more robust and able to add features without introducing complexity, we will refactor it with an **OOP** object-oriented programming paradigm using **TypeScript classes**
		- I call these TypeScript classes instead of JavaScript classes since TypeScript offers more features than JavaScrip classes, e.g. public, private, protected access modifiers, full properties, type validation, code-completion and intellisense you don't get with JavaScript classes
	- (A) create **PageManager** class and sanitize the idCode so the first character is always capitalized
		- I called the class **PageManager** instead of e.g. PageCreator since **createPage()** will be a method on the class, but we can easily create other methods on the same class called **deletePage()** and **renamePage()**
		- **PageManager.ts**
			--------------------------------------------
			import * as tools from './tools';

			export class PageManager {
				private idCode = '';

				constructor(idCode:string) {
					this.idCode = tools.capitalizeFirstCharacter(idCode);
				}

				public getIdCode() {
					return this.idCode;
				}
			}			
			--------------------------------------------
		- **tools.ts**
			------------------------------------------------
			export const capitalizeFirstCharacter = (text: string) => {
				return text[0].toUpperCase() + text.slice(1);
			}			
			------------------------------------------------
		- **cp.ts**
			-----------------------------------------
			const pageManager = new PageManager(pageIdCode);
			console.log(pageManager.getIdCode());			
			-----------------------------------------
		- it now capitalizes the idCode sent##idcodealsewyastcap
	- (B) handle the case that idCode could be **undefined**
		- the way we are going to handle this is:
			- if the constructor of the class receives anything invalid, it will **throw an error with a message**
			- where the class is called, it will be called in a **try block** which has a **catch block** to catch the error and output a helpful message to the user
		- **PageManager.ts**
			--------------------------------------
			constructor(idCode:string) {
				if (!idCode) {
					throw Error("invalid idCode");
				}

				this.idCode = tools.capitalizeFirstCharacter(idCode);
			}			
