	- !!! decide to first build **appContext** to load all application data in one place which any page or component can use
		- in this step, we want to build a page "Manage Flashcards" that fetches and displays flashcards from the backend
		- we could, of course, simply fetch the data from that page
		- but we know we are building a larger application that we will like to extend later
			- and we will have other pages which access the same data as well
			- e.g. this "Manage Flashcards" page will be an admin page which will not be available on the read-only site at Vercel
			- at Vercel, we will have e.g. a **Flashcards** page on which the user can view and flashcards as finished, etc.
				- we don't want to have to load flashcards from this page as well
				- hence the best decision is to create an AppContext for all pages and components
		- in general, any app with more than one page should load all its appData in one place
			- this is an example of **separation of concerns** where you have
				- **one entry point for external data** into your app 
				- so you know the external data coming into your app is **validated, cleaned and well-structured**
