- **>>> 1. Create environment variable so that site knows if it exists locally or at Vercel**
	- this application is local full-stack crud and online read-only CDN
		- that means when the app is running **on your local machine, you can edit the database** (JSON files) 
		- but when you publish the code to **Vercel**, the site will run from a CDN without a backend, and will hence be **read-only**
		- this means at Vercel that **some pages will not be visable** and **some functionality will not be available**
	- therefore **the site needs to know where it is**
		- for this we will make an **environment variable** called **VITE_ENV**
		- all environment variables used by a Vite website need to begin with **VITE_**
		- when the site is running on your **local machine**, it will equal **development**
		- when the site is running at **Vercel**, it will equal **production**
	- environment variables are stored in a **.env** file in the **root directory**
		- .env files will also contain sensitive information such as database connections strings
		- therefore .env files should never be checked into your GitHub repository
		- that is why we always list **.env** in the **.gitignore** files
		- at hosting providers like **Vercel**, environment variables are entered on the web usually in the **settings section**
		- this is how you can have a different value for e.g. **VITE_ENV** locally than you have for the same variable at Vercel##envfilekasdjf
	- let's create an environment variable and display it on the welcome screen so we can see that it has different value on our local machine than on at Vercel
		- make sure **.gitignore** file lists **.env**##thenvfgit
		- create **.env** file in the root directory - **note: no quotation marks**
