- **>>> 2. Understand the difference between your local site and your online site**
	- note: the **Manage Flashcards** page on your Vercel site *appears* to work
		- the reason is that in our AppContext code, which is running at Vercel, we have our **local backend URL** saved
		- if view from anyone else's machine, this page on your Vercel site will not be able to get any flashcards
			- because on their machine, they have no API running on port 4206
		- if you **stop your local site** (CTRL-C in terminal) so that nothing is running on port 4206 on your machine, then your Vercel site will not work##itappearstowork
	- we could, of course, host a backend API at Render or some other hosting provider, and change our backend URL to that API when running at Vercel
		- this is how, in fact, distributed applications work on the Internet
		- but to do this, we would have to **implement full security** on our backend such as authentication, authorization, hashing passwords, data verification, data cleansing, JWT tokens or session/cookies, etc. in order to **protect our POST, PUT, PATCH and DELETE routes** which would be exposed to the open Internet for all bots and ill-intended people to freely access, thus filling our database with spam or deleting it entirely
	- but our current application has the intention to be the following
		- on **local computer**: a full-stack CRUD application in which we can easily create, delete and edit data via website pages and forms
		- at **Vercel**: a high-security, high-speed but read-only site
		- this is not only (1) a **useful type of application**, it is also (2) a good way to **practice the complexity of full-stack API web development** without having to yet deal with databases and online security
	- therefore we need to **hide all CRUD-related pages when the site is at Vercel**
		- this is why we created the environment variable
