- **what we will do**
	- we'll create a Node/Express API that reads from a database
		- the API will be hosted at Render
		- and the database (Postgres) will be hosted at Render
	- so this database will not be local on the machine, e.g. it won't be
		- **lowdb** that saves to a local JSON file 
		- **SQLite** that saves to a local SQLite file
		- **MySQL** that saves to a local MySQL server
		- **Postgres** that saves to a local Postgres server
	- rather, the database will be an **online database hosted at Render**
		- Render offer Postgres as a database to host for free for a limited time (3 months)
		- so it is a Postgres database, but not installed locally on our machine
	- this means that we will be able to use it
		- from our API when it is local on our machine
		- from our API when it is hosted at Render
	- instead of communicating directly with the Postgres database with its native SQL commands
		- we will use an ORM (object-relational mapper) so that we simply ask it for information from the database
			- and the ORM converts our requests into SQL commands and sends us arrays of objects back
		- we have a wide choice of ORMs to use
			- [Prisma](https://www.prisma.io) - works well with TypeScript, supports most SQL databases and MongoDB, newer, lightweight, popular in tutorials
			- [TypeORM](https://typeorm.io) - less support for TypeScript, higher learning curve
			- [Sequelize](https://sequelize.org) - older, works only with SQL databases, some TypeScript support
			- [Drizzle](https://orm.drizzle.team) - an up-and-coming ORM, supports TypeScript, fast
			- [MicroORM](https://mikro-orm.io) - TypeScript support, not as popular, supports both SQL and NoSQL databases such as MongoDB
		- in this project, we will use **Prisma**
