- **>>> 7. Convert JavaScript to TypeScript**
	- often when you create a quite project, you use JavaScript because it is easier and faster at first
	- but if you want to build that project into a larger application, you quickly reach the point where it is advantageous to use TypeScript
		- for instance, note we have two variables in our application already that are called **skill**
			- _skill = skills without **id** and **whenCreated** fields
			- skill = skills with **id** and **whenCreated** fields
			- this could very easily lead to confusion and errors
			- when converting to TypeScript, we will define an interface for each 
				- so that if you try to use e.g. **_skill** where **skill** is expect, TypeScript will catch it
		- in addition, since we are going to publish this to Render
			TypeScript will give us the added protect that it will not publish to Render if there are any TypeScript errors
		- also, while developing we get intellisense of all our variables
