- **background**
	- to ensure security and security in your applications
	- it is important to validate and cleanse all data that arrives from any external source
		- there are 5 major sources of external data for a frontend website##themmm5sources
	- even when you control the external source, e.g. an API
		- data may be hacked and manipulated as it travels over the network or Internet
		- you should never trust external data
	- TypeScript does not protect you from mal-formed external data
		- TypeScript only ensures **internal data integrity**
		- TypeScript only **protects you from yourself**, e.g. you say that a function receives string, then you send it a number
		- but in production, TypeScript **compiles to JavaScript**, so it is JavaScript which runs in your production code
		- so if your frontend recieves employee data from an API
			- and the API sends a number as a firstName
			- and your JavaScript code tries to run firstName.toUpperCase()
			- then you will get an error in run time
			- TypeScript is no longer present in your production code to catch this error
		- therefore we need a tool that remains in production code to validate/cleanse external data
			- this tool is **Zod**
	- **Zod** is a TypeScript-first schema declaration and validation library
		- Zod enables you to create schemas which you use to check if external data is correctly shaped
		- TypeScript types can be created from Zod schemas
		- Zod has validation features that go beyond TypeScript, e.g.
			- you can ensure a variable is not only a string, but a certain length, or satisfies a regex
			- you can ensure that a number is between a certain range
