- **>>> 3. Understand why TypeScript does not protect you from mal-formed external data at runtime**	
	- although we use TypeScript in the frontend
		- it only protects us from making **internal** mistakes regarding the types
		- we are basically telling it, "we expect members to have two fields, one a number and one a string"
		- TypeScript can only warn us if we do something contrary to what we ourselves say we expect		
		- for instance, if we use **substring()** on a property which we said we expect to be a number
			- **PageWelcome.tsx**
				-------------------------------------------
				<li key={member.id.substring(0,3)}>{member.name}</li>
				-------------------------------------------
				- then we get an error
				- and in this case, JavaScript gets an error as well
				- so we would see this error even if we weren't using TypeScript##showstwoerrors
		- but in this instance, if we use **substring()** on the number property **id** for a condition which we as a developer don't reproduce with out test data:
			- **PageWelcome.tsx**
				---------------------------------------------
				<ul className="list-disc ml-6">
					{members.map((member: IMember) => {
						return (
							<React.Fragment key={member.id}>
								{member.name.length < 30 ? (
									<li>{member.name}</li>
								) : (
									<li>{member.id.substring(0,5)}</li>
								)}
							</React.Fragment>
						);
					})}
				</ul>				
				---------------------------------------------
				- we don't get an error
					- the site works
					- there is no error in the browser console
					- if we were using JavaScript, there would be no error in VSCode either
				- the reason we are not getting an error is
					- at the moment, none of our member names happen to be longer than 30
				- again: **JavaScript** wouldn't inform you about this potential bug at all
					- only after you publish your site
					- your customers who use names longer than 29 characters would get errors
					- and they would inform you of the bug (or not)
				- luckily we are using **TypeScript**, which informs us **at developer time** that we are **violating our own rules**, i.e.
					- we said in our interface that we expected the id of member to be a number
					- yet we forgot, were sloppy, and used id as a string
					- here we see that TypeScript protects us from our own carelessness##errorwhencustom
		- however, TypeScript only informs you of type conflicts **between the types in your code and the types you stated you expect** 
			- it does not inform you of type conflicts **between the types in your code and the types that exist at runtime**
			- let's demonstrate that this is true
			- let's imagine that you changed your member display to show the id in a different format and used a number function, e.g.
				- **PageWelcome.ts**
					--------------------------------------------------------------
					<li key={member.id}>
						ID #{member.id.toFixed(3)} - {member.name}
					</li>
					--------------------------------------------------------------
				- your output looks like this:##theformatidid
			- and let's imagine that the backend API does not belong to you
			- and then let's imagine that the backend team decided to change the **id** from an auto-increment number such as **1**, **2**, **3** to a suuid, e.g. a string such as **I82jj4**
				- (BACKEND) **index.ts**
