					const members = [
						{
							id: "28jj21",
							name: "Robert Hammerschmidt"
						},
						{
							id: "ii34ja",
							name: "Angela Wasserturm"
						}
					];
					----------------------------------------------------
			- your frontend now looks like this:
				- your site is broken
				- yet TypeScript is not informing you of any error##therrorwithidid
		- so let's say you realize this error and correct it by updating your interface 
			- **interfaces.ts**
				--------------------------------------
				export interface IMember {
					id: string,
					name: string;
				}
				--------------------------------------
			- typescript will now inform you of the error##theerrorrtypeidmm
			- and you change how you display the **string id** with a string function
			- **PageWelcome.ts**
				--------------------------------------
				<li key={member.id}>
					ID #{member.id.toUpperCase()} - {member.name}
				</li>
				--------------------------------------
			- this merely tells TypeScript that **you expect id to be a string**
			- and as long as id actually is a string at runtime, your site will work
			- and because ids are now being sent as strings, your site now looks like this:##thenewsuudid
		- but a change in the backend types may not be the only reason you receive non-conform data 
			- let's mock that there is some kind of transition error during the response
