- **background**
	- this how to will show you how to implement authentication in your website using sessions and cookies
	- we will first build a **backend** that has a
		- `/users/login` route which allows a user to identify themselves
			- if unsuccessul, this route will return a 401
			- if successful
				- a cookie will be set in the browser which has a time-to-live of e.g. 20 minutes
				- this route will return a 200 along with the object of the user that just logged in
		- `/users/current` route which gets the current user
			- while the cookie is still active, this route will return the object of the user who is logged in
			- when the cookie expires, this route will return a 401
		- `/users/logout` route which logs the user out
			- the user object is set to null
			- this route returns a 200
	- then we will build a **frontend** which will allow the user to log in and stay logged in until the cookie expires
		- when the site loads, a request is sent to `/users/current`
			- if a 200 and user object are returned, that user is set as the current user
				- the name of the user is displayed
				- the user has access to privileged pages
		- if logged out, user can log in
			- a request is sent to `/users/login` along with the form data fields login/password
			- if a 200 and user object are returned, that user is set as the current user
				- the name of the user is displayed
				- the user has access to privileged pages
		- if logged in, user can log out
			- user name is no longer displayed
			- priviledged pages are no longer available
	- before we begin, let's get an idea of how **session/cookies** vs. **JWT** work
		- [Understand the difference between session-cookies and JWT tokens](https://tanguay-eu.vercel.app/howtos/680)
	- code is here:
		- https://github.com/edwardtanguay/et729-session-cookie-fullstack (2024-02-13 preparation)
		- https://github.com/edwardtanguay/et730-session-cookie-fullstack (2024-02-14 live-coding)
